@node "Nice_Story" "A nice story..."
@next "System_Requirements"
@prev "Main"

                              @{fg highlight}A  NICE@{fg text}     ^ ^
                                          o o
                                @{fg highlight}STORY@{fg text}      |
                                         \___/
                                           _


 One hot day, during summer 1995, I (OgniX) was on the mixer of Italia
 Network (it WAS the most trendy radio station in Italy) playing
 "@{"The Colour Inside" link "Copyright" 0}"© by TiPiCal©. Like a rain drop on a summer's hot
 afternoon, an idea came out: it's the Intel Outsiiide... I sang these
 magic words over the song. GREAT IDEA!!!
 I told my idea to some friends of mine (Amiga Freaks or near).
 At the beginning I didn't think about making it with a tracker on Amiga:
 I thought to make it in the recording studio of my friend Pera.
 Later, once we've found out the lyrics for the song, we thought that it
 could be done with ProTracker.
 We recorded the voice for the song (thanks to Jon Bat, Pera's brother) at
 Italia Network studios in Udine; we started to digitize vocals into
 ProTracker on 8th October 1995ad.
 Here we found the first problems on max sample length (64 KB) and number
 of instruments (31): really poor quality of samples and no enough space
 for the remaining instruments.
 For the moment the project has been stopped because of my studies at
 university and because of my friend Pera's music projects in progress.
 Not even during Xmas we re-started working on "The Intel Outside Project"
 because of my troubles.
 From the beginning of February 1996ad we re-put our hands on this stuff:
 little modifications to lyrics to fit metric needs better, drawing the
 cover, editing of this guide file and, last but not least, the composing
 of the track.
 Due to limitations of ProTracker we decided to use OctaMED instead (sorry
 mod lovers!).
 Although this choice, sampling quality (read sampling frequency) couldn't
 be so high because we had got to digitize a lot of vocal parts: Chip RAM
 is limited (please read @{"System Requirements" link "System_Requirements" 0}).
 It was finished on Sunday 12th May 1996 at 1:22am! (Eeerk! 8^O )
 Well, now enjoy it!

 P.S. I you wish to make a remix of "The Intel Outside" please @{"contact us" link "Contact" 0}
      first (see @{"Copyright Stuff" link "Copyright" 0}).
      At the moment some remixes are planned: a house/garage one by me
      (OgniX), another commercial dance version by Pera, a gabber one
      by Redd Kaa, a jungle implementation by Sheffra of JointMen and,
      maybe, a soft underground/house version (Joey Negro style) by me.
      If this module will be appreciated, we'll release its following one
      (just in our minds -> thanks to Neil Martin).
@endnode

@node "System_Requirements" "System Requirements"
@next "Copyright"
@prev "Nice_Story"

                           @{fg highlight}SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS@{fg text}
                           ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

 Due to use of a lot of samples, this MED module (OctaMED Pro V5.0 - MMD1)
 can be played only on Amigas with at least 2 MB of Chip RAM (ECS Agnus 8375
 or AGA).

 Note 1  To use the player included in the archive you have to copy the
         OctaPlayer.library into your LIBS: drawer.

         e.g.   Copy The_Intel_Outside/OctaPlayer.library to LIBS:
         or     Copy The_Intel_Outside/OctaPlayer.library to DH0:Libs

 Note 2  If you have a bare A500, A600, A2000 or an A1200 with 2 MB
         Chip RAM only buy some RAM. (Ok, you haven't got enough money ;)
         Well, to be serious, for listening to this incredible module (!)
         8-> you have to:
         1) disable booting with Startup-Sequence by selecting the
            relative option in the bootup menu (press both mouse buttons
            after a reset - for Amiga OS 2.0 and above) or by pressing
            <CTRL-D> to stop execution (Amiga OS 1.X).
         2) Once in the CLI type the complete path of the player followed
            by the complete path of the module; press <RETURN>.

         e.g.   DH0:Music_Utils/OctaMEDPlayer DH0:Modules/Intel_Outside.med
@endnode

